---
import LabLayout from '../layouts/LabLayout.astro';
import CardRow from '../components/lab/CardRow.astro';
import EvalTable from '../components/lab/EvalTable.astro';

// TODO: replace with the real Luma event URL and date before launch (one-line
// swaps). LUMA_URL falls back to the Boston meetup calendar until then.
const LUMA_URL = 'https://luma.com/tair';
const EVENT_DATE = 'Date to be announced';
const SUBSCRIBE_URL = 'https://theairuntime.com/subscribe';

const breaks = [
  { term: 'Stale', body: 'true once, not anymore, and the source is cached.' },
  { term: 'Unsupported', body: 'the evidence is missing, walled, or does not actually back the claim.' },
  { term: 'Conflicting', body: 'two sources disagree on a field that matters.' },
  { term: 'Extraction-drift', body: 'the agent grabbed the wrong field, or the wrong company.' },
];

const trustLayer = [
  { term: 'Guard', body: 'check each claim is fresh, supported, and the right shape before it ships.' },
  { term: 'Degrade', body: 'hand over the records you can stand behind and name the gaps, instead of padding the list with junk.' },
  { term: 'Observe', body: 'emit a trace per record: where it came from, what was checked, what was rejected and why.' },
];

const evalHeaders = ['Group', 'Count', 'Verdict', 'Tests'];
const evalRows = [
  ['Clean', 10, 'accept', 'keeps good leads'],
  ['Stale', 5, 'reject or review', 'outdated evidence'],
  ['Unsupported', 5, 'reject or review', 'missing or weak evidence'],
  ['Conflicting', 5, 'review', 'source disagreement'],
  ['Extraction-drift', 5, 'reject', 'wrong field or entity'],
];

const passBar = [
  'bad-record recall at or above 85 percent',
  'clean-record precision at or above 80 percent',
  'evidence coverage 100 percent on accepted records',
  'zero unsupported accepted claims',
  'a reason on every rejection',
];

const runOfShow = [
  'Customer frame',
  'Apify source layer',
  'Improve the trust core against the Dirty Thirty',
  'Eval checkpoint',
  'Add the policy filter and run live',
  'Founder report and teardown',
  'Show-and-tell',
];
---
<LabLayout
  title="Field Lab 01: A Reliability Layer for Web-Grounded Agents"
  description="Build and prove a reusable trust layer for a web-grounded growth agent: a design-partner sourcing agent on Apify, graded on whether its leads are safe to act on."
  ogImage="/og-01.png"
>
  <!-- 1. Hero -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <p class="mono-label eyebrow">Field Lab 01 · Boston · with Apify</p>
      <h1>A Reliability Layer for Web-Grounded Agents</h1>
      <p class="sub">Build a design-partner sourcing agent on Apify, then prove which leads are safe to act on.</p>
      <p class="promise">
        You will not leave with a lead-gen toy. You will leave with a reusable trust layer for
        web-grounded agents and an eval that proves whether it works.
      </p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn" href={LUMA_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Register on Luma</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href={SUBSCRIBE_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Subscribe</a>
      </div>
      <ul class="chips">
        <li>In person, Boston</li>
        <li>Hands-on build</li>
        <li>Bring a laptop</li>
        <li>{EVENT_DATE}</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 2. The founder problem -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <h2>The founder problem</h2>
      <blockquote class="story">
        <p>
          A founder has a product and not enough customers, so they point an agent at the web to find
          who to sell to. The agent returns fifty clean leads. The founder emails all fifty. A third
          bounce, several were never a fit, two of the companies shut down last year. The list looked
          done. It was not.
        </p>
        <p>
          That gap, between a list that looks done and a list you can act on, is what this Field Lab is
          about. The web data part is easy. Knowing which of it to trust is the job.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 3. What this actually is -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <h2>What this actually is</h2>
      <div class="col">
        <p>
          This is not a lead-generation session. It is about the reliability layer around a
          web-grounded agent: where the data came from, whether the evidence holds, and what to do when
          it does not. Lead generation is just the first use case. The trust layer is the artifact, and
          it works for any agent that makes claims off the web.
        </p>
        <p>
          Two layers, and only one is the product. The trust core is source-agnostic: it takes a claim
          and its evidence and decides whether it is true and supported right now. The policy filter
          sits on top and decides whether a true claim fits what the founder asked for. The core is the
          reusable piece. The fit logic stays on top so it never contaminates it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 4. The shared scenario -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <h2>The shared scenario</h2>
      <div class="col">
        <p>
          The whole room works the same problem. A seed to Series A B2B SaaS founder selling a
          developer-facing product, no growth hire, who needs a weekly list of qualified design-partner
          candidates.
        </p>
        <p>
          The fit profile, which feeds the policy layer: US-based B2B SaaS, 50 to 300 people, a
          developer-facing product, a contact who is an engineering leader, and a real reason to reach
          out now.
        </p>
        <p>
          You build an agent that returns a prospect list where every field traces to a source that
          currently supports it. Plausible is not verified.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 5. The four ways web data breaks -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <h2>The four ways web data breaks</h2>
      <CardRow items={breaks} />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 6. What you build, the trust layer -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <h2>What you build, the trust layer</h2>
      <CardRow items={trustLayer} />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 7. The bar, the Dirty Thirty -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <h2>The bar, the Dirty Thirty</h2>
      <div class="col">
        <p>
          Thirty frozen records with known answers, ten clean and twenty each planted with a specific
          break. Your guard is graded on two numbers, not one: did it catch the bad records, and did it
          keep the good ones. An agent that rejects everything scores perfectly on the first and fails
          the second, so it fails. That is the point.
        </p>
      </div>
      <EvalTable headers={evalHeaders} rows={evalRows} />
      <p class="passbar-lead">Pass bar:</p>
      <ul class="passbar">
        {passBar.map((p) => <li>{p}</li>)}
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 8. What you leave with -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <h2>What you leave with</h2>
      <div class="col">
        <p>
          A working sourcing agent. A reusable, source-agnostic trust core. A thin growth policy filter.
          The thirty-case eval harness. Your own measured precision and recall. A founder-facing trust
          report. And a teardown that says, not "I built an agent," but "I built a reusable reliability
          layer for web-grounded agents, benchmarked it against a planted trap set, and produced a
          safe-to-act-on number." That is a portfolio artifact, not a demo.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 9. How it runs -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <h2>How it runs</h2>
      <ol class="runlist">
        {runOfShow.map((step, i) => (
          <li><span class="n">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, '0')}</span>{step}</li>
        ))}
      </ol>
      <p class="setup">
        Bring any coding assistant you already use. Claude Code, Copilot, Cursor, and Codex are all
        fine. The repo is plain Python on the Apify SDK, so the tool you write with does not change the
        build. You need a working Python runtime and a model key. A thirty-second smoke test in the
        pre-work confirms both before you arrive.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 10. Run with -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <h2>Run with</h2>
      <div class="col">
        <p>
          Run with Apify, who provide the data plane: the Actors and datasets that feed the agent. The
          AI Runtime Field Lab owns the scenario, the reliability bar, the trap set, and the published
          write-up.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 11. Close -->
  <section class="sec close">
    <div class="lab-container">
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn" href={LUMA_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Register on Luma</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href={SUBSCRIBE_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Subscribe</a>
      </div>
      <div class="newhere">
        <p>New to The AI Runtime? Start here:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://theairuntime.com">The newsletter</a>, production lessons every week.</li>
          <li><a href="/briefs">Field Briefs</a>, the problem library.</li>
          <li><a href="/investigations/design-partner-sourcing/">Investigation 01</a>, the field report behind this build.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!--
    12. POST-EVENT, BUILD LATER (stub, do not remove).
    After the event, append these as real sections. Content add, not a rebuild:
      - Results: the eval outcomes (precision, recall, coverage) per build.
      - Failure modes: what broke and why.
      - What changed after hardening: before vs after the guard.
      - The reusable pattern: the source-agnostic trust core, generalized.
      - The teardown and repo link.
  -->
</LabLayout>

<style>
  /* Buttons: the lab design system has no button styles (investigations uses
     plain links), so define them here in lab tokens. */
  .btn {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 0.7rem 1.3rem;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--accent);
    background: var(--accent);
    color: #fff;
    transition: background 140ms ease, color 140ms ease, border-color 140ms ease;
  }
  .btn:hover { background: #c64708; border-color: #c64708; text-decoration: none; }
  .btn-ghost { background: transparent; color: var(--text); border-color: var(--border-strong); }
  .btn-ghost:hover { background: transparent; color: var(--accent); border-color: var(--accent); }
  .btn:focus-visible, a:focus-visible { outline: 2px solid var(--accent); outline-offset: 2px; }

  .hero { padding: 4rem 0 2.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .eyebrow { margin: 0 0 1rem; color: var(--accent); }
  .hero h1 { max-width: 18ch; }
  .sub {
    max-width: 40rem;
    margin: 0.9rem 0 0;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: var(--text-2);
  }
  .promise {
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.2rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: var(--bg-2);
    border-radius: 0 var(--radius-sm) var(--radius-sm) 0;
    color: var(--text);
    font-size: 1.02rem;
  }
  .cta-row { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.75rem; margin-top: 1.75rem; }
  .chips {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 1.5rem 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.5rem;
  }
  .chips li {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.74rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--text-2);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px;
    padding: 0.25rem 0.7rem;
  }

  .sec { padding: 3rem 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .sec h2 { margin: 0 0 1.25rem; }
  .col { max-width: 42rem; }

  .story {
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin: 0;
    padding-left: 1.2rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--border-strong);
  }
  .story p { color: var(--text); }
  .story p + p { margin-top: 1rem; }

  .passbar-lead {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text-3);
    margin: 1.75rem 0 0.6rem;
  }
  .passbar { max-width: 42rem; margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; }
  .passbar li { margin: 0.3rem 0; color: var(--text-2); }

  .runlist { list-style: none; margin: 0; padding: 0; display: grid; gap: 0.5rem; max-width: 42rem; }
  .runlist li {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 0.9rem;
    padding: 0.7rem 1rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    background: var(--bg-2);
    color: var(--text);
  }
  .runlist .n { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--accent); }

  .setup {
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin: 1.75rem 0 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.2rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: var(--bg-2);
    border-radius: 0 var(--radius-sm) var(--radius-sm) 0;
    color: var(--text-2);
    font-size: 0.98rem;
  }

  .close { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .newhere { margin-top: 2.5rem; }
  .newhere > p { color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
  .newhere ul { padding-left: 1.2rem; margin: 0; }
  .newhere li { margin: 0.4rem 0; color: var(--text-2); }
</style>
